@node NorthC "North 'C' V1.3"
A @{"public domain" link PDShareware} version of @{"'C'" link C}, not completely @{"ANSI 'C'" link ANSI} compatable,
but extremely good none-the-less, produced by S.Hawtin I believe.

Translates 'C' into @{"Assembly Language" link AssemLang}.
@endnode

@node A68k
A @{"public domain" link PDShareware} @{"680x0" link CPU} machine code @{"compiler" link compiler} by Charlie Gibbs.

Translates 680x0 @{"Assembly Langauge" link AssemLang} into @{"object code" link object}.
@endnode

@node Blink
A @{"public domain" link PDShareware} linker, produced by "The Software Distillery."

Translates pieces of @{"object code" link object} into a functional executable file.
@endnode

@node Compiler
A computer program that translates a computer langauge into a
lower level language.  (See @{"High-Level Langauges" link HLL} and
@{"Low-Level Langauges" link LLL}.)
@endnode

@node Object "Object Code"
A type of file produced by a @{"compiler" link compiler} from a @{"high level language" link HLL},
somewhere between a high level language and @{"executable" link executable} code,
though still requires work to be performed on it by a @{"linker" link linker} before
it can be 'run'.

(This isn't a very good description, but if you are reading this then
giving the full technical explanation probably wouldn't help much.)
@endnode

@node HLL "High-Level Language"
A form of computer program that is intended to be fairly
comprehendable to humans; which without translation a computer
itself would not understand.
@endnode

@node LLL "Low-Level Language"
A form of computer language that, although not very comprehendable to
humans, is much more understandable to a computer.
@endnode

@node Executable
A type of file that can be 'executed' or 'run' by a computer; a
program!
@endnode

@node CPU "680x0"
The central-processing unit, the 'thinking' (so-to-speak) part of a
computer, inside the Amiga is based around the 68000 series
of chips.
@endnode

@node Fred "Fred Fish"
Fred Fish puts together one of the best known and regarded
collection of @{"Public Domain" link PDShareware} and @{"Shareware" link PDShareware} software available
for the Commodore Amiga series of computers; the Fred "Fish" disk
collection.
@endnode

@node PDShareware "Public Domain, Shareware, Freeware etc. Software"
Public Domain (P.D.) Software is generally software written and
released to be freely distributed, unlike commercial software for
which monies must be payed.

Shareware/Freeware is generally software to be distributed freely,
but charges must not be made by any other third parties for further
distribution other than by the author. In Shareware, if the program is
used, a contribution is required to be given to the author; normally
a small and very reasonable fee, for which the author will
generally give back-up, support, assistance and details
of future versions.  Much Shareware software available is
considerably better than thier commercial counterparts.


NOTE:
P.D. & Shareware are usually intended for non-commercial uses
only, and the authors of the programs often have clauses
to this effect.  There are also other strict clauses in some
software packages, such that any further distrubition of the
software must not be charged for, and that the files must
not be changed any further etc.
@endnode

@node C "The 'C' Language"
A very good, extremely popular, @{"portable" link portable}, @{"high-level language" link HLL}
used throughout the computer world.  Although it is a high-level
langauge, it can be relatively easily converted into a
@{"low-level language" link LLL} quickly, efficiently, producing @{"executable" link executable}
code that will generally run much faster than code produced by
many other high-level langauges.
@endnode

@node AssemLang "Assembly Language"
A very very @{"low-level language" link LLL}, the nearest step you can get to
the language that the computer understands - but still retaining
some human 'understandability'.
@endnode

@node portable "Portable"
'Portability', with respect to computing, means the ability to
translate a program designed for use on one computer system
to be usable on another computer system.
@endnode

@node UUE "UUE Encoding Decoding Algorithms"
A technique for turning @{"binary" link BBB} @{"files" link files} using all 8-@{"bits" link BBB}
into @{"ASCII" link ASCII} files using only 7-bits, so that these files can
be easily transmitted, for instance, over @{"Electronic Mail" link email}.
@endnode

@node ANSI "ANSI 'C'"
Agreed standard for the @{"'C'" link C} programming language, to attempt
to remove the differences between various implementations of the
languge, and to increase the langauges @{"portability" link portable}.
@endnode

@node cproto "'C' Function Prototyping"
In good @{"high-level langauges" link HLL} it is possible to define exactly how
various functions of the program should be used, to help stop @{"bugs" link bugs}
being designed into the program.  In @{"ANSI 'C'" link ANSI} the method
used is 'C' Function Prototyping.
@endnode

@node Kickstart "Kickstart"
The name of the @{"operating system" link OS} used on the Commodore Amiga
series of computers.  Many versions have been in regular use, most
commonly from around 1.1 to 3.0.
@endnode

@node OS "Operating System"
The special set of computer programs working within a computer to perform
the basic required tasks of running the computer; also supplying various
commonly used tools for other programs to run on the computer.
@endnode

@node ASCII "ASCII"
(A)merican (S)tandard (C)ode for (I)nformation (I)nterchange.

An agreed standard for the computer alphabet.  Each 'letter' being
one @{"byte" link BBB} in size, but only using 7 @{"bits" link BBB} of the byte.
@endnode

@node BBB "Bytes, Binary and Bits!"
A 'byte' is a computer number, a piece of a computers memory.  Generally
8 'bits' in size.  A program would be made up of a number of 'bytes'.

A 'bit' is a single element of a piece of a computer memory, having
only two states, representing 'binary' 1 or 'binary' 0.

'Binary' is the number system that computers work with, base 2.  We
work and think in base 10; we count from 0 to 9, then 10 to 19, then
20 to 29 and so on - computers count from 0 to 1, then 10 to 11, then
100 to 101, 110 to 111 etc - each '1' or '0' is represented by
a 'bit'.

'Binary' is also a term used to describe @{"files" link files} where each
'byte' uses all the available 8-'bits'; as apposed to an @{"ASCII" link ASCII}
file where only 7-'bits' are used.

A 'checksum' is a special number used for testing that a file has not
become corrupted somehow.  Effectively, one adds up all the bytes in
a file, and takes a few of the lower (least significant) bits of the
total produced and uses this as a checksum byte.
@endnode

@node Archive "Archive"
A single @{"file" link files}, in which a collection of other files is
stored. An archive is also generally compressed, to use less @{"bytes" link BBB}
to be smaller in length - to make transmitting/receiving the program
cheaper/faster/easier.
@endnode

@node Archiver
A program for manipulating @{"archives" link archive}, generally allowing the
user to add, extract, remove, examine/list @{"files" link files} in an archive.
@endnode

@node files "Files"
A named collection of @{"bytes" link BBB}, representing either a
computer program, or data (information) of some sort.
@endnode

@node Internet "Internet"
A popular world wide @{"network" link network}, allowing all sorts of different forms of
links and communications between computers and thier users, including
@{"electronic mail" link email}.  Allows computers to 'talk' to each-other.
@endnode

@node network
Computers linked up together to be able to communicate with
each-other.
@endnode

@node email "Electronic Mail (E-Mail)"
A computer letter made up of @{"ASCII" link ASCII} characters, sent from
one person on a computer to another person, via a @{"network" link network},
just like normal Post-Service Mail, but existing within the memories
of computers rather than on paper - and much much faster!
@endnode

@node snailmail "Snail Mail"
An 'in' computer term to describe normal Postal-Service mail.
@endnode

@node guiarc "GuiArc"
An extremely good @{"freeware" link PDShareware} program that allows the user to use
@{"archivers" link archiver}, extracting/adding @{"files" link files} from @{"archives" link archive}, all under a
@{"graphical user interface" link gui}, rather than having to operate the archivers
via a @{"CLI" link CLI}.  Written by Patrick van Beem.
@endnode

@node arctypes
An a @{"file" link files} for the @{"GuiArc" link GuiArc} program that tells
it how to use various @{"archiving" link archiver} systems.
@endnode

@node gui "Graphical User Interface"
A recent step away from the traditional means of operating computers
via a @{"CLI" link CLI}.  On computer system using an @{"operating system" link OS}
based around a graphical user interface (such as the Commodore Amiga),
commands are given to the computer by the user using
common-sense/intuition; by selecting appropriate @{"Icons" link icons} that
represent your desired instructions to the computer on the screen.
@endnode

@node script "Script"
A set of computer commands, generally @{"CLI" link CLI} commands.
@endnode

@node icons "Icons"
Pictorial representation of a command/instruction/object.
@endnode

@node cli "Command Line Interface"
A system of intructing the computer your wishes by entering a series
of textual commands.
@endnode

@node dir "Directory"
A place on a computer where @{"files" link files} are stored.
